Radiation-induced life span alteration of Drosophila lines with genotype 
differences.

Moskalev A(1).

Author information:
(1)Institute of Biology, Komi Science Center of Russian Academy of Sciences, 
Kommunisticheskaja St. 28, Syktyvkar 167982, Russia. amoskalev@list.ru

The research shows that unirradiated Drosophila lines with defects of DNA 
repair, antioxidant protection and apoptosis have higher speed of ageing, than 
wild type line. At the same time, depending on the line genotype, the 
irradiation results in change of life span. Mechanism of postponed effect of low 
dozes of ionizing radiation on the life span is elaborated. As cells with 
weakened protection will accumulate damages and will be exposed to ageing with 
the greater speed, than steady cells, their radio-induced elimination at early 
development stages will result in delay of age-dependent changes and will lower 
speed of ageing. In the subsequent irradiated generations the given somatic 
answer to stress (hormesis) may be replaced by negative genetic effects on the 
population level (shorter life span).

